{"title":"Men’s Tour de France 2024: Route, how to watch and all you need to know","link":"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-de-france-route-live-tv-guide-startlist-stage-by-stage","date":1717776966000,"content":"<p><a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk\">Cyclist</a><br />\n<a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-de-france-route-live-tv-guide-startlist-stage-by-stage\">Men’s Tour de France 2024: Route, how to watch and all you need to know</a></p>\n\n<p>The 2024 <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/tour-de-france\" target=\"_blank\">Tour de France</a> is almost upon us. The race will start in Florence, Italy on Saturday 29th June and finish in Nice on Sunday 21st July, with Visma-Lease a Bike’s <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-de-france-2022-recap\" target=\"_blank\">Jonas Vingegaard</a> on track to attempt to defend his title against rival <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/tadej-pogacar\" target=\"_blank\">Tadej Pogačar</a>, former teammate <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/primoz-roglic\" target=\"_blank\">Primož Roglič</a> and Belgium’s great hope <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/remco-evenepoel\" target=\"_blank\">Remco Evenepoel</a>.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>With a Grand Départ in Italy for the first time and the finish outside Paris for the first time because of the Olympics, it will be a historic edition whatever happens during the race. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>It also means that it will be full gas racing from start to finish, with the opening stage from Florence to Rimini going straight in at the deep end with 3,600m of climbing on a hilly stage through Tuscany, Emilia-Romagna and San Marino – which will become the 13th foreign country to host the Tour. The finale in Nice won’t be a <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-de-france-final-stage-procession\" target=\"_blank\">procession like we normally see in Paris</a> either, instead the 2024 Tour will finish with a time-trial starting in Monaco and finishing at the Place Masséna, just off the Promenade des Anglais in Nice.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>To separate riders between those stages (although let’s hope not too much to keep the drama going all the way to that final day à la <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-de-france-history-greg-lemond-snatches-the-closest-tour-ever\" target=\"_blank\">Greg LeMond in 1989</a>) will be not only an array of France’s toughest climbs including the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/col-du-galibier-tour-de-france\" target=\"_blank\">Col du Galibier</a>, Puy Mary, <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/classic-tour-de-france-climbs-col-du-tourmalet\" target=\"_blank\">Col du Tourmalet</a> (yes, again), Hourquette d’Ancizan, Pla d’Adet, <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/col-de-peyresoude\" target=\"_blank\">Col de Peyresourde</a>, <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/plateau-de-beille\" target=\"_blank\">Plateau de Beille</a>, Col du Noyer, <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/col-de-vars-cycling\" target=\"_blank\">Col de Vars</a>, <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/classic-climbs-cime-de-la-bonette\" target=\"_blank\">Cime de la Bonette</a>, Isola 2000, <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/summits-and-switchbacks-big-ride-turini\" target=\"_blank\">Col de Turini</a> and the Col de la Couillole (and breathe), but also a gravel stage with 14 sectors around the Champagne gravel roads, as seen in the <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-de-france-femmes-2022-stage-4-gallery-reusser\" target=\"_blank\">2022 Tour de France Femmes</a>.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>All in all it’s officially eight flat stages for Mark Cavendish to get win #35, four hilly stages for spice, seven mountain stages for whittling down the GC, four summit finishes for maximum drama and two time-trials for Jonas Vingegaard to cement win #3.</p>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/pro-cycling-sponsors\">Who actually are the Tour de France team sponsors 2024?</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/buying-guides/best-cycling-french-alps\">Best places to cycle in the French Alps</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-de-france-femmes\">Tour de France Femmes 2024 route announced ft. Alpe d’Huez and a mini Monument</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/worldtour-team-bikes\">All the WorldTour team bikes, tech and kit 2024</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article><article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n                          <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/cime-de-la-bonette-cycling\">Classic climb: Cime de la Bonette, Europe’s highest pass… or is it?</a>\r\n                       </h4>\r\n                    </div>\r\n                 </article></div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <span></span><span></span><span></span>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                        <div>\r\n                                            <div>\r\n                                                <div></div>\r\n                                            </div>\r\n                                        </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                    <div>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                        <span></span>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                    </div>\r\n                                </div>\r\n                                \r\n                            </div>\r\n                        </div>\r\n                        </div>\n\n\n<h2>Tour de France 2024: Key information</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"647\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/Tour-de-France-2023-goding-10-970x647.jpg\" alt=\"cyclist bowing on bike\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/Tour-de-France-2023-goding-10-970x646.jpg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/Tour-de-France-2023-goding-10-300x200.jpg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/Tour-de-France-2023-goding-10-768x512.jpg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/Tour-de-France-2023-goding-10-1536x1024.jpg 1536w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/Tour-de-France-2023-goding-10-2048x1365.jpg 2048w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/Tour-de-France-2023-goding-10-750x500.jpg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/Tour-de-France-2023-goding-10-1140x760.jpg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/Tour-de-France-2023-goding-10-465x310.jpg 465w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/Tour-de-France-2023-goding-10-620x413.jpg 620w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/07/Tour-de-France-2023-goding-10-350x233.jpg 350w\" /><figcaption>Jasper Jacobs/Belga/GodingImages</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Dates:</strong> Saturday 29th June to Sunday 21st July 2024<br /><strong>Grand Départ:</strong> Florence, Italy<br /><strong>Finale:</strong> Nice, France<br /><strong>Total elevation gain: </strong>52,230m<br /><strong>Total prize money: </strong>€2.3million<br /><strong>UK television coverage:</strong> ITV4, Eurosport, GCN+, S4C<br /><strong>2023 winner:</strong> Jonas Vingegaard (Jumbo-Visma)<br /><strong>Most overall wins: </strong>Jacques Anquetil, Bernard Hinault, Miguel Indurain, Eddy Merckx (all 5)<br /><strong>Most stage wins: </strong>Eddy Merckx, Mark Cavendish (34)</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Tour de France 2024 route</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"970\" height=\"970\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/tour-de-france-2024-map-970x970.jpeg\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/tour-de-france-2024-map-970x970.jpeg 970w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/tour-de-france-2024-map-300x300.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/tour-de-france-2024-map-150x150.jpeg 150w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/tour-de-france-2024-map-768x768.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/tour-de-france-2024-map-75x75.jpeg 75w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/tour-de-france-2024-map-350x350.jpeg 350w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/tour-de-france-2024-map-750x750.jpeg 750w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/tour-de-france-2024-map-1140x1140.jpeg 1140w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2023/10/tour-de-france-2024-map.jpeg 1200w\" /><figcaption>ASO</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>While the route doesn’t go to Paris, it does flirt with its Île-de-France region with stages in nearby Orléans and Troyes. The lack of Paris finish does mean that the transfers between stages look less drastic, which is a good thing. And not finishing with a procession is exciting. Maybe they should sack Paris off altogether – can 2025 finish in Brittany?</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Tour de France 2024 stage-by-stage preview</h2>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 1: Saturday 29th June, Florence – Rimini, 206km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-1.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 1\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-1.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-1-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-1-768x461.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-1-750x450.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Officially the hardest opening stage in Tour de France history, this beast begins by crossing Florence’s Ponte Vecchio and takes on a load of hills, including the climb up to San Marino, to create early gaps.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 2: Sunday 30th June, Cesenatico – Bologne, 199.2km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"577\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-2.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 2\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-2.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-2-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-2-768x462.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-2-750x451.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Starting in Marco Pantani’s hometown of Cesenatico, it’s another hilly stage through Emilia-Romagna, finishing with two goes round a circuit including the Côte de San Luca, which is traditionally used in the Giro dell’Emilia.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 3: Monday 1st July, Plaisance – Turino, 230.8km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-3.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 3\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-3.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-3-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-3-768x461.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-3-750x450.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Sprint day #1 – should Mark get the job done early or keep some suspense for the story?</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 4: Tuesday 2nd July, Pinerolo – Valloire, 139.6km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-4.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 4\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-4.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-4-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-4-768x461.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-4-750x450.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Yes it’s only Stage 4 and it’s mountains. And not just any mountains, it’s the Galibier and probably the race’s earliest<em> </em>‘Souvenir Henri Desgrange’ prize, although it won’t<em> </em>be the highest summit of this year’s race.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 5: Wednesday 3rd July, Saint-Jean-de-Maurienne – Saint-Vulbas, 177.4km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-5.jpeg\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-5.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-5-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-5-768x461.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-5-750x450.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Despite being firmly in mountain region still, Stage 5 takes us through the valley for the second sprinters’ day.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 6: Thursday 4th July, Mâcon – Dijon, 163.5km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"577\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-6.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 6\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-6.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-6-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-6-768x462.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-6-750x451.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Let’s hope Mark Cavendish can cut the mustard in Dijon, it’s sprint three.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 7: Friday 5th July, Nuits-Saint-Georges – Gevrey-Chambertin, 25.3km, ITT</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-7.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 7\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-7.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-7-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-7-768x461.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-7-750x450.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The first time-trial of the race comes in wine country, but no champagne will be sprayed yet (that’s Stage 9). It’s set to be flat apart from a 1.6km, 6.1% average kicker near the end. Someone tell Tadej Pogačar that it’s not enough to warrant a bike change.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 8: Saturday 6th July, Semur-En-Auxois – Colombey-les-Deux-Églises, 183.4km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-8.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 8\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-8.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-8-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-8-768x461.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-8-750x450.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>There are five categorised climbs on this one but nothing too crazy that a sprint can be ruled out. </p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 9: Sunday 7th July, Troyes – Troyes, 199km with 14 gravel sectors</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"577\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-9.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 9\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-9.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-9-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-9-768x462.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-9-750x451.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Stage 9 will be a day of reckoning for Jonas Vingegaard, who struggled on the cobbles of Roubaix in 2022, as now-cobbles legend Pogačar will surely look to put the pressure on his Danish rival over these 14 gravel sectors. For a taste of what’s in store, look back on <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q-zvd5OMjo4\" target=\"_blank\">Stage 4 of the 2022 Tour de France Femmes</a>.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 10: Tuesday 9th July, Orléans – Saint-Amand-Montrond, 187.3km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-10.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 10\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-10.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-10-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-10-768x461.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-10-750x450.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Race director Christian Prudhomme is making an early prediction of echeleons in this one, so no doubt it’ll be a slow bunch sprint day. If not, Cavendish has done the business in the crosswinds before.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 11: Wednesday 10th July, Évaux-les-Bains – Le Lioran, 211km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-11.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 11\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-11.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-11-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-11-768x461.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-11-750x450.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>It doesn’t look that impressive, but apparently there’s 4,350m of elevation gain on this one, including the brutal Puy Mary Pas de Peyrol climb. It’s the only day in the Massif Central.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 12: Thursday 11th July, Aurillac – Villeneuve-sur-Lot, 203.6km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-12.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 12\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-12.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-12-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-12-768x461.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-12-750x450.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>It’s probably a breakaway day with hills including the opposite way up where the final time-trial of the 2022 race went at the beautiful Rocamadour, but a versatile sprinter could take it.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 13: Friday 12th July, Agen – Pau, 165.3km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"577\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-13.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 13\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-13.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-13-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-13-768x462.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-13-750x451.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>This will likely be a sprinter that can climb with a few hills as the teams will surely put the pressure on.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 14: Saturday 13th July, Pau – Saint-Lary-Soulan Pla d’Adet, 151.9km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-14.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 14\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-14.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-14-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-14-768x461.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-14-750x450.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>It’s a big boy. Three brutal climbs, finishing in the exact spot that Raymond Poulidor won in 1974, apparently. Will Mathieu van der Poel have to talk about his grandpa again?</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 15: Sunday 14th July, Loudenvielle – Plateau de Beille, 197.7km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-15.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 15\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-15.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-15-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-15-768x461.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-15-750x450.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Get the turbos out lads, it’s straight into the Peyresourde. Five categorised climbs across 198km with 4,850m of elevation. Count your lucky stars this isn’t the Étape stage.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 16: Tuesday 16th July, Gruissan – Nimes, 188.6km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-16.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 16\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-16.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-16-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-16-768x461.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-16-750x450.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>It’s a sprint, thankfully they’ve had a rest day to prepare. If Cav hasn’t done it by now then pray for teeth, nails, hair and hearts worldwide.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 17: Wednesday 17th July, Saint-Paul-Trois-Châteaux – Superdévoluy, 177.8km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-17.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 17\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-17.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-17-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-17-768x461.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-17-750x450.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>It looks like it’s one long 178km climb, so that means the breakaway has no chance. Pogačar uphill sprint win loading.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 18: Thursday 18th July, Gap – Barcelonette, 179.5km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"577\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-18.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 18\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-18.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-18-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-18-768x462.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-18-750x451.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Prudhomme reckons this is a sprint day, but considering it’s officially classed as ‘hilly’, Cavendish won’t be contesting this one. There are a few hills to play with so it’s more likely to be a breakaway or a <em>puncheur</em>.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 19: Friday 19th July, Embrun – Isola 2000, 144.6km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"577\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-19.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 19\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-19.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-19-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-19-768x462.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-19-750x451.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>That’s another humongous day. Not only is the Cime de la Bonette the highest point of the race, it’s the highest road in France and third highest in Europe.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 20: Saturday 20th July, Nice – Col de la Couillole, 132.8km</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"577\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-20.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 20\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-20.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-20-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-20-768x462.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-20-750x451.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The final mountain stage looks set to be epic. That’s how a Tour de France profile should look, stunning. Early doors it’s the TV climbs like the Turini to get the blood pumping, and it culminates in the 15.7km climb up the Couillole to see if the fight for yellow will be decided in a final day time-trial.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>This one<em> </em>is the 2024 Étape du Tour. Some day out that will be.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Stage 21: Sunday 21st July, Monaco – Nice, 33.7km, ITT</h3>\n\n\n\n<figure><img width=\"960\" height=\"576\" src=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-21.jpeg\" alt=\"tour de france 2024 profile stage 21\" srcset=\"https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-21.jpeg 960w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-21-300x180.jpeg 300w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-21-768x461.jpeg 768w, https://dqh479dn9vg99.cloudfront.net/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2024/06/tour-de-france-2024-profile-stage-21-750x450.jpeg 750w\" /><figcaption></figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>It could well be the most exciting finish to a Tour de France since <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/in-depth/tour-de-france-history-greg-lemond-snatches-the-closest-tour-ever\" target=\"_blank\">1989</a>, although that hype probably means it’ll be sewn up by Stage 6. It’s by no means flat, climbing up the 8.1km, 5.6% average La Turbie out of Monaco and the 1.6km, 8.1% side of the Col d’Èze before descending into Nice. Could an Englishman win on the Promenade des Anglais? Probs not, sorry.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Tour de France 2024: How to watch on live TV and streaming</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>The 2024 Tour de France will be available to watch in the UK on ITV4 and ITVX for free, and Eurosport 1 for those with the channel. You can also stream it on <a href=\"https://auth.discoveryplus.com/gb/product?flow=purchase&amp;videoAssetId=6021174\" target=\"_blank\">Discovery+</a> for £6.99 per month with the basic package, which includes cycling and all other Eurosport programmes. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>It is being broadcast across 198 countries, but it’s not being shown in your country, you may be able to watch coverage using a VPN – Virtual Private Network – which allows users to mask their IP address and watch geo-blocked content, provided they don’t need to pay for a subscription. This is also helpful for watching paid-for coverage while travelling abroad in countries without access.  </p>\n\n\n\n<p>One such example is <a href=\"https://go.expressvpn.com/m5yJGZ\" target=\"_blank\">ExpressVPN</a>, which is very <a href=\"https://www.independent.co.uk/advisor/vpn/expressvpn-review\" target=\"_blank\">well reviewed</a>, helps users to find a way to watch cycling without having to pay for broadcasters services, and costs £5.36 per month, with three months free. Other options include <a href=\"https://go.skimresources.com/?id=205647X1684865&amp;xs=1&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fnordvpn.com%2F\" target=\"_blank\">NordVPN</a>, <a href=\"https://go.skimresources.com/?id=205647X1684865&amp;xs=1&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fsurfshark.com%2F\" target=\"_blank\">Surfshark</a> and <a href=\"https://go.skimresources.com/?id=205647X1684865&amp;xs=1&amp;url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.kaspersky.co.uk%2F\" target=\"_blank\">Kapersky</a>.</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>How to watch the Tour de France in Europe</h3>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Europe: </strong>Eurosport<br /><strong>Basque Country: </strong>EiTB<br /><strong>Belgium: </strong>RTBF, VRT<br /><strong>Czech Republic: </strong>Česká Televize<br /><strong>Denmark: </strong>TV2<br /><strong>France: </strong>France TV<br /><strong>Germany: </strong>ARD, Discovery+<br /><strong>Ireland: </strong>TG4<br /><strong>Italy: </strong>Discovery+, RAI Sport<br /><strong>Luxembourg: </strong>RTL<br /><strong>Netherlands: </strong>Discovery+, NOS<br /><strong>Norway: </strong>TV2<br /><strong>Portugal: </strong>RTP<br /><strong>Scandinavia: </strong>Discovery+<br /><strong>Slovakia: </strong>RTVS<br /><strong>Slovenia: </strong>RTV SLO<br /><strong>Spain: </strong>RTVE<br /><strong>Switzerland: </strong>SRG-SSR<br /><strong>United States: </strong>Discovery+, Eurosport, ITV<br /><strong>Wales: </strong>S4C</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>How to watch the Tour de France in North and Central America</h3>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Canada: </strong>FloBikes<br /><strong>Caribbean: </strong>ESPN<br /><strong>Latin America: </strong>ESPN<br /><strong>United States: </strong>NBC Sports, TV5 Monde</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>How to watch the Tour de France in South America</h3>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Colombia: </strong>CaracolTV<br /><strong>Latin America: </strong>ESPN<br /><strong>South America: </strong>TV5 Monde</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>How to watch the Tour de France in Asia</h3>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>China: </strong>CCTV, Zhibo TV<br /><strong>Japan: </strong>J Sports<br /><strong>Middle East: </strong>BeIN Sports, TV5 Monde<br /><strong>Southeast Asia: </strong>Eurosport</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>How to watch the Tour de France in Oceania</h3>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Australia: </strong>SBS<br /><strong>New Zealand: </strong>Sky Sport</p>\n\n\n\n<h3>How to watch the Tour de France in Africa</h3>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Africa: </strong>TV5 Monde<br /><strong>North Africa: </strong>BeIN Sports<br /><strong>Subsaharan Africa:</strong> Supersport</p>\n\n\n\n<h2>Tour de France 2024 start list</h2>\n\n\n\n<div><p><em>Data powered by <a href=\"https://firstcycling.com/race.php?r=17&amp;y=2024&amp;k=8\" target=\"_blank\">FirstCycling.com</a></em></p></div>\n\n\n\n<p><em>For all Tour de France-related news, head to our <a href=\"https://www.cyclist.co.uk/tags/tour-de-france\" target=\"_blank\">hub page</a></em></p>\n\n\n<div>\r\n                <div>\r\n                   <div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <h4><span>Related Posts</span></h4>\r\n                      </div>\r\n                      <div>\r\n                         <div>\r\n                            <div>\r\n                            <article>\r\n                    <div>\r\n                       <h4>\r\n 